_No response_

### Description

Writing APIs that accept `ResourceOptions` as an argument is suboptimal. Not sure if there could anything be done about it or if it's just a limitation of TypeScript. See example below:

When using the following signature, all types are figured out correctly:
```ts
const resourceRef = resource({
  request: () => {
    const id = numberSignal();
    if (id == null) {
      return undefined;
    }
    return { id };
  },
  loader: ({ request: { id } }) => {
    return Promise.resolve(String(id))
  }
})
```
The type of `id` in the loader's request argument is correctly inferred as `number`. The type of `resourceRef` is `ResourceRef<string>`.
Notice how I didn't have to specify any types explicitly. Everything just works.

However, if options are declared separately, things fall apart:

```ts
const resourceOptions = {
  request: () => {
    const id = numberSignal();
    if (id == null) {
      return undefined;
    }
    return { id };
  },
  loader: ({ request: { id } }) => {
    return Promise.resolve(String(id))
  }
} satisfies ResourceOptions<any, any>;

const resourceRef = resource(resourceOptions);
```

With this, the type of resourceRef is correct: `ResourceRef<string>`. However, the type of `id` in loader's request argument is `any`.

Also, this might have something to do with the comment about an issue with `NoInfer`: https://github.com/angular/angular/issues/58871#issuecomment-2498195267

### Proposed solution

Making generic types optional by  providing default `any` value makes it slightly easier to work with, but overall does not provide the dev experience I'm after.

```ts
export interface ResourceOptions<T = any, R = any> {
  request?: () => R;
  loader: ResourceLoader<T, R>;
  equal?: ValueEqualityFn<T>;
  injector?: Injector;
}
```

Need guidance from someone more experienced with TypeScript.

### Alternatives considered

Create a function that takes options and returns them. This seems silly since it seemingly just adds boilerplate, but it works:

```ts
function createResourceOptions<T, R>(options: ResourceOptions<T, R>): ResourceOptions<T, R> {
  return options;
}

const resourceOptions = createResourceOptions({
  request: () => {
    const id = numberSignal();
    if (id == null) {
      return undefined;
    }
    return { id };
  },
  loader: ({ request: { id } }) => {
    return Promise.resolve(String(id))
  }
});

const resourceRef = resource(resourceOptions);
```
All types are figured out correctly.

